ggplot(data=penguins) # creates an empty graph

ggplot(data=penguins,
       mapping=aes(x=flipper_length_mm,y=body_mass_g)) # maps a specific variable 

# onto the x axis, another variable onto the y axis
ggplot(data=penguins,
       mapping=aes(x=flipper_length_mm,y=body_mass_g))+
  geom_point() # adds a layer of points to the plot 
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

We now want to incorporate the different species into our plot by separating the respective points into different colors. This is an aesthetics things, so lets put this condition in the aesthetic mapping function.

ggplot(data=penguins,
       mapping=aes(x=flipper_length_mm,y=body_mass_g,color=species))+
  geom_point() 
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

We now want to add a smooth curve displaying the relationship b/w body mass and flipper length into our plot. This is a new graph (a curve) using a new geom (smooth), so add it.

ggplot(data=penguins,
       mapping=aes(x=flipper_length_mm,y=body_mass_g,color=species))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

We now have curves, but we want only one curve for the entire dataset, as opposed to separate curves for each species, so move this aesthetic over to the geom smooth function.

ggplot(data=penguins,
       mapping=aes(x=flipper_length_mm,y=body_mass_g))+
  geom_point(mapping=aes(color=species))+
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

For accessibility purposes, add shapes to the different points that represent different species.

ggplot(data=penguins,
       mapping=aes(x=flipper_length_mm,y=body_mass_g))+
  geom_point(mapping=aes(color=species,shape=species))+
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

We can now add labels to our plot by using the labs function.

ggplot(data=penguins,
       aes(x=flipper_length_mm,y=body_mass_g))+
  geom_point(aes(color=species,shape=species))+
  geom_smooth()+
  labs(title="Body Mass and Flipper Length",
       x="Flipper Length (mm)",
       y="Body Mass (g)",
       color="Species",
       shape="Species")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Q: Make a scatterplot of bill_depth_mm vs bill_length_mm. Describe the relationship b/w these two variables.

A: There is no relationship b/w bill depth and length. Bill length flunctuates around 45mm on avg, regardless of bill depth.

ggplot(data=penguins,
       aes(x=bill_depth_mm,y=bill_length_mm))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth()+
  labs(title="Bill Depth vs Length",
       x="Bill Depth (mm)",
       y="Bill Length (mm)")

Q: What does the na.rm argument do in geom_point()? What is the default value of the argument? Create a scatterplot where you successfully use this argument set to TRUE.

A: The default is na.rm=FALSE, so dont remove missings.

ggplot(data=penguins,
       aes(x=species,y=bill_length_mm))+
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data=penguins,
       aes(x=species,y=bill_length_mm))+
  geom_point(na.rm=TRUE)

ggplot(data=penguins,
       aes(x=species,y=bill_length_mm))+
  geom_point(na.rm=FALSE)
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(penguins,aes(x=species))+geom_bar()

Q: Make a bar plot of species of penguins, where you assign species to the y aesthetic. How is this plot different?

A: Flips the axes of the graph around.

ggplot(penguins,aes(y=species))+geom_bar()

Q: How are the following two plots different? Which aesthetic, color or fill, is more useful for changing the color of the bars?

A: Simply outlines the bars vs fills the bars. The ladder is more useful.

ggplot(penguins,aes(x=species))+geom_bar(color="red")

ggplot(penguins,aes(x=species))+geom_bar(fill="red")

ggplot(penguins,aes(x=species,y=body_mass_g))+geom_boxplot()
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

ggplot(penguins,aes(x=island,fill=species))+geom_bar()

ggplot(penguins,aes(x=island,fill=species))+geom_bar(position="fill")
